# Why Are Armenia and Azerbaijan at War? A Comprehensive Analysis

## Introduction

The conflict between Armenia and Azerbaijan, centered on the disputed region of Nagorno-Karabakh, is one of the most protracted and complex territorial disputes in the post-Soviet space. Despite a ceasefire agreement in 1994, the region has witnessed recurrent violence, culminating in a significant escalation in 2020. This report aims to provide an in-depth, structured, and factual analysis of the reasons behind the Armenia-Azerbaijan war, drawing from multiple reliable sources and recent developments. The report also includes military comparisons and geopolitical considerations to contextualize the conflict.

---

## Historical Background of the Conflict

Nagorno-Karabakh is a mountainous region internationally recognized as part of Azerbaijan but predominantly populated by ethnic Armenians. The roots of the conflict trace back to the early 20th century and were exacerbated during the Soviet era when the Nagorno-Karabakh Autonomous Oblast (NKAO) was established within the Azerbaijan Soviet Socialist Republic despite its Armenian majority ([BBC News, 2020](https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-54324772)).

As the Soviet Union began to collapse in the late 1980s, the Nagorno-Karabakh regional parliament voted to join Armenia, sparking ethnic clashes and eventually a full-scale war after both Armenia and Azerbaijan declared independence from Moscow. The war (1988-1994) resulted in approximately 30,000 deaths and displaced around one million people, mostly Azerbaijanis ([NBC News, 2020](https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/why-are-armenia-azerbaijan-fighting-nagorno-karabakh-n1240833)).

The 1994 Russian-brokered ceasefire left Nagorno-Karabakh and seven adjacent districts under Armenian control, though the territory remained internationally recognized as Azerbaijani. Since then, Nagorno-Karabakh has been governed by a self-declared republic backed by Armenia but unrecognized internationally ([BBC News, 2020](https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-54324772)).

---

## Core Causes of the Conflict

### 1. Territorial Dispute

The primary cause is the territorial claim over Nagorno-Karabakh. Azerbaijan insists on its territorial integrity, including Nagorno-Karabakh, whereas Armenia supports the self-determination of the ethnic Armenian population in the region. The conflicting claims have been the trigger for recurrent violence and war.

### 2. Ethnic and Cultural Identity

Nagorno-Karabakh's population is majority Armenian, and Armenians view the region as part of their historic homeland, often referred to as "Artsakh." Conversely, Azerbaijanis consider Nagorno-Karabakh integral to their national identity and trace cultural heritage to the Karabakh Khanate of the 18th century ([NBC News, 2020](https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/why-are-armenia-azerbaijan-fighting-nagorno-karabakh-n1240833)).

### 3. Religious Differences

Armenia is predominantly Christian, while Azerbaijan is majority Muslim. Although religion is often used for propaganda, the conflict is primarily driven by secular nationalism rather than religious animosity ([NBC News, 2020](https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/why-are-armenia-azerbaijan-fighting-nagorno-karabakh-n1240833)).

### 4. Soviet Legacy and Geopolitical Maneuvering

The Soviet policy of "divide and rule" placed Nagorno-Karabakh within Azerbaijan despite its Armenian majority, sowing seeds for future conflict. Post-Soviet power vacuums and the involvement of regional powers such as Russia and Turkey have further complicated the dispute ([Falco, 2018](https://carc.sps.ed.ac.uk/mapping-the-nagorno-karabakh-conflict/)).

