## Geopolitical Dynamics

### Regional Powers and Alliances

- **Turkey**: Strongly supports Azerbaijan politically, militarily, and culturally, viewing Azerbaijan as a "brotherly" Turkic nation. Turkey's involvement includes military exercises and alleged support with Syrian mercenaries during the 2020 conflict ([NBC News, 2020](https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/why-are-armenia-azerbaijan-fighting-nagorno-karabakh-n1240833)).

- **Russia**: Maintains a military base in Armenia and is allied with Armenia through the Collective Security Treaty Organization (CSTO). However, Russia also maintains good relations with Azerbaijan and supplies arms to both sides. Russia brokered the 1994 ceasefire and the 2020 peace deal, deploying peacekeepers to monitor the truce ([BBC News, 2020](https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-54324772)).

- **Iran**: Supports Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh due to geopolitical rivalry with Turkey and concerns over regional stability ([Falco, 2018](https://carc.sps.ed.ac.uk/mapping-the-nagorno-karabakh-conflict/)).

### International Mediation Efforts

The OSCE Minsk Group, co-chaired by Russia, France, and the United States, has mediated peace talks since 1992 but has failed to produce a lasting settlement. The 2020 conflict revealed the limitations of international mediation, especially with Turkey's overt involvement and the U.S.'s limited engagement ([BBC News, 2020](https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-54324772)).

---

## Recent Developments and Escalations

### 2020 War and Ceasefire

In late September 2020, Azerbaijan launched a large-scale offensive to retake Nagorno-Karabakh and surrounding territories, supported overtly by Turkey. The conflict lasted six weeks, causing thousands of deaths and displacing tens of thousands more. The war ended with a Russian-brokered ceasefire on November 10, 2020, resulting in Azerbaijan regaining control over several adjacent districts and the strategic city of Shusha within Nagorno-Karabakh ([BBC News, 2020](https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-54882564)).

### Post-War Tensions

Despite the ceasefire, tensions remain high. Azerbaijan continues to pressure Armenia on issues like prisoner exchanges and territorial access, including demands for Armenia to recognize Nagorno-Karabakh as part of Azerbaijan and to allow transit through the Syunik province to the Nakhichevan exclave. Armenia faces internal political instability due to dissatisfaction with the ceasefire terms ([Poghosyan, 2021](https://www.armenian-institute.org/)).

